# Project: Apiculture Income Analysis

This project examines the determinants of income among small-scale beekeepers in Meru County, Kenya using survey data and econometric analysis.

## Tools Used

- ggplot2
- readxl
- MASS
- dplyr

# Data Loading

```{r include=FALSE}
library(readxl)

apiculture_data <- read_excel("data/public_apiculture_data.xlsx")
```

# Income Distribution

```{r}
table(apiculture_data$ANNUALINCOME)
```

# Data Visualization

```{r}
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(apiculture_data, aes(x = ANNUALINCOME)) +
  geom_bar() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    title = "Income Distribution of Beekeepers",
    x = "Income Category",
    y = "Frequency"
  ) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
```

# Ordered Logistic Regression

```{r include=FALSE}
library(MASS)

# Fix income category
apiculture_data$ANNUALINCOME[
  apiculture_data$ANNUALINCOME == "100001-"
] <- "100001+"

# Convert to ordered factor
apiculture_data$ANNUALINCOME <- factor(
  apiculture_data$ANNUALINCOME,
  levels = c("<5000", "5000-10000", "11000-20000", "21000-100000", "100001+"),
  ordered = TRUE
)

# Convert predictors
apiculture_data$TYPEOFHIVES <- factor(apiculture_data$TYPEOFHIVES)
apiculture_data$FORMALBEEKEEPINGTRAINING <- factor(apiculture_data$FORMALBEEKEEPINGTRAINING)

# Run model
model <- polr(
  ANNUALINCOME ~ TYPEOFHIVES + FORMALBEEKEEPINGTRAINING,
  data = apiculture_data
)
```

# Key Findings

- Majority of beekeepers fall within low-income categories.
- Formal beekeeping training improves income outcomes.
- Traditional hives are associated with lower productivity and earnings.
- Modern beekeeping practices improve commercialization potential.

